Ref: KERMIT-10, GLXLIB et al

I still do not feel that I can give a "good" time estimate at this
point.  A lot depends on which direction you would like me to pursue.
The choices that I see at present are:

  1) Carve GLXLIB (Galaxy) out of KERMIT and re-write the text
     I/O segment. [Time estimate, 3-months minimum, 1 person].

  2) Make a working GLXLIB, or as much as seems necessary to handle
     command scanning, text/file manipulations, terminal i/o and
     inter-process communications (including memory management).

     THEN, work the bugs out of this interfaced with KERMIT.
     [Time estimate, 1 month for GLXLIB, 1-2 weeks for KERMIT]

  3) Re-IMPLEMENT KERMIT from one of the other versions into SAIL
     or BLISS... [Time estimate, 1 month minimum, probably 2-3
     depending upon the convertability of other versions].
     Note:  The TOPS-10 version is currently the closest to the
     TOPS-20 version, and would probably provide better results
     under option 2 (above).

I have proceeded into option 2 above, as it seems most reasonable.
Of the dozen or so modules in GLXLIB, I have identified the areas
which need changes, and in 3 modules completed all or 99% of the
necessary fixes.  Left to fix are, TRMOP. calls (to AUXCALs), some
FILOP. calls (to CHANIOs), some PPN/Username fixups and the IPCF/
Interrupt system changes.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

My time estimates are, "ROUGH", and by the end of next week, I could
give you better details.  If you have time tomorrow, I can lay it out
for you in more detail.  I'd rather NOT write it out, because it would
take me LESS time to complete the project by simply FIXING the things
which need changes, than to enumerate ALL of the minor things as I
find them.

(end of week -- means one week from today! )
/Carl


